GPU-accelerated Visualization: A Primer on Exploratory Data Analysis at Scale

Presenter: Randy Zwitch (@randyzwitch)
Location: Enterprise Applications of R (EARL) 2018 (Boston)
GitHub: https://github.com/omnisci/EARL2018

OmniSci Immerse Dashboard

The data for this example comes from the EPA Air Markets Program, which provides hourly pollution readings from each generator in the United States via FTP download.

1. Define a Connection Using ODBC

Currently, OmniSci does not have a dedicated R package; to connect to OmniSci from R, we will use ODBC.

Defining the table reference can take a while on the first run, but once the table reference is created, the actual dplyr statements will return instantly, even over 720 million records and 23 columns.

library(dplyr)
library(odbc)
con <- dbConnect(odbc::odbc(), "OmniSci Production")
ppe <- tbl(con, "powerplantemissions")
colnames(ppe)

 [3] "orispl_code"             "unitid"                 
 [5] "op_time"                 "gload_mw"               
 [7] "sload_1000lbs"           "so2_mass_lbs"

[11] "so2_rate_measure_flg"    "nox_rate_lbs_per_mmbtu"

2. Full Table Summary

To get a quick feel for the data, we can run a simple query to calculate the number of power plants per state and some averages for the amount of power generated (gload_mw) and average levels of pollution (so2, nox, co2):

ppe %>%
  group_by(state) %>% 
  summarize(records = n(),
            powerplants =         n_distinct(orispl_code),
            mean_gload =          mean(gload_mw, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_sload =          mean(sload_1000lbs, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_so2 =            mean(so2_mass_lbs, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_so2_per_mmbtu =  mean(so2_rate_lbs_per_mmbtu, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_nox_lbs =        mean(nox_mass_lbs, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_nox_per_mmbtu =  mean(nox_rate_lbs_per_mmbtu, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_co2 =            mean(co2_mass_tons, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_co2_per_mmbtu =  mean(co2_rate_tons_per_mmbtu, na.rm=TRUE),
            mean_heat =           mean(heat_input_mmbtu, na.rm=TRUE)
            ) %>%
    collect() %>%
    arrange(desc(powerplants)) -> summary_by_state
summary_by_state

3. Instant Access to Record-Level Data

In the prior example, we summarized across the entire table in relatively short order (~375ms). This is due to the massive bandwidth and core density provided by multiple GPUs. However, actual analysis is usually done with subsets of data, and OmniSci will be equally as fast (if not faster) here:

ppe %>% 
  filter(facility_name == "Colbert" & 
         ts >= '2000-01-01 00:00:00' & ts <= '2000-01-07 23:00:00') %>%
  select(ts, co2_mass_tons) %>%
  collect() -> generator_perf
generator_perf

Being able to retrieve data in 300ms across nearly a billion rows, we can use OmniSci as a caching/computation engine. While the Vega plot displayed below is static, with some htmlwidgets magic or a Shiny app/flexdashboard, we could evaluate any power plant we wish.

library(vegalite)
vegalite() %>%
  cell_size(600, 300) %>%
  add_data(generator_perf) %>%
  encode_x("ts", "temporal") %>%
  encode_y("co2_mass_tons", "quantitative") %>%
  mark_line()

4. ButWe Could Do Even Better If There Were an R Package

While ODBC allows plug-and-play into many analytics tools, ODBC is the slowest way to work with OmniSci. Especially if your R session happens to be on the same server as OmniSci (as is this demo).

Sharing Memory Between Processes

OmniSci supports in-process communication (IPC), both CPU and GPU, based on Apache Arrow. So instead of serializing the results, sending them to R and having R build a data frame using ODBC, the Apache Arrow bindings for R (in-development by Romain Francois and others) will allow for taking the results straight out of OmniSci and directly to R!

Why Not Render Visualizations on the GPU?

You canand OmniSci does! OmniSci uses the Vega visualization grammar to specify charts, and renders them on the GPU whenever it makes sense. This is even more efficient than IPC, as the data never leaves the GPU and only a rendered PNG file is returned.

While we might have been able to use reticulate for this example to use the OmniSci python package (pymapd) that has this implemented, but installing 50+ python dependencies to get R functionality feels sub-optimal.

Looking For Collaborators!

If large scale, super-fast computation and visualization using GPUs within R interests you, Id love to hear from you! At its core, OmniSci is an open-source company, and Id love to collaborate with anyone interested in making a native R package a reality.
